95":"1395","1340":"1340","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1300":"circa 1300","Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland":"Skerry, County Antrim, Ierland","Tir-Eoghain, Tyrone , Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Ierland",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ierland","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ierland"},"en":{"about 1300–1347":"about 1300–1347","1290–1359":"1290–1359","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1264–1354":"1264–1354","–1337":"–1337","7 February 1337":"7 February 1337","from 1325 to 1345":"from 1325 to 1345","1264":"1264","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1300":"about 1300","Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland":"Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland","Tir-Eoghain, Tyrone , Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Neill,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Seamus, Siobhan, Dermot, Liam, Nuala, Bridie, Brigid, Conor, Fintan, John Patrick.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Néill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niall</i>’, an Irish personal name possibly derived from <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’ (see   Neil  ).","History: Bearers of this surname mostly claim descent from Niall Noígíallach (Niall of the Nine Hostages), a legendary king of Ireland who flourished in the 5th century. His descendants, the Ui Neill dynasty, dominated Ireland, on and off, from the 6th to the 10th century. The surname itself can be traced with some confidence to one of these descendants, namely Niall Glúndubh mac Aodha (died 919), High King of Ireland from 911 to 919, with a power base in Tyrone, Ulster."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Neall","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"McNelis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Brendan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Niallghuis</b> ‘son of <i>Niallghus</i>’, a personal name (intended as complimentary) composed of the personal name <i>Niall</i> (see   O'Neill  ) + <i>gus</i> ‘vigor’. In Irish the combination of [k] and [n] was generally pronounced [kr], Anglicized as the variants   McCreless   and   McCrillis  ."]},{"name":"O'Neal","meanings":["Irish (Longford, Down): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"O'Niel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Odneal","meanings":["Perhaps an irregular variant of Irish   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Nealon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Nialláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Niallán</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>Niall</i>, see   O'Neill  ,   Neil  ."]},{"name":"O'Neil","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Conn, Donal, Liam, Siobhan, Aileen, Eamon, Michael Patrick, Seamus, Sean Patrick, William Sean.","Irish (Mayo, Tipperary): variant of   O'Neill  ."]},{"name":"Neil","meanings":["Scottish, English (Lancashire), and Irish (Munster): from the Gaelic personal name <i>Niall</i> (genitive <i>Néill</i>), possibly derived from Irish <i>néal</i> ‘cloud’. In most cases the name probably represents a shortened form of the derived patronymics   McNeill   or the comparable Irish   O'Neill  .","English: variant of   Neal  ."]},{"name":"O'Neel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Neill  ."]}]},{"name":"Énri","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Henry</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Henry","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."]}]},{"name":"macBrian","type":"LAST","meanings":["Irish: Mac, son, and Brian, from Britain, meaning son of the country of the Brith, or painted people"],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Énri macBrian O'Neill, Prince of Tir-Eoghain was born about 1300, in Tyrone, County Galway, Ireland as the son of Brian Macaedo O'Neill, Prince of Tyrone and Eleanor Magennis. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1347, in County Tyrone, Ireland, at the age of 48, and was buried in County Tyrone, Ireland."},"et":{"about 1300–1347":"umbes 1300–1347","1290–1359":"1290–1359","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1264–1354":"1264–1354","–1337":"–1337","7 February 1337":"7. veebruar 1337","from 1325 to 1345":"1325 kuni 1345","1264":"1264","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1300":"umbes 1300","Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland":"Skerry, County Antrim, Iirimaa","Tir-Eoghain, Tyrone , Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Iirimaa",", Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Iirimaa","County Tyrone, Ireland":"County Tyrone, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"about 1300–1347":"noin 1300–1347","1290–1359":"1290–1359","1291–1345":"1291–1345","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1340–1395":"1340–1395","1264–1354":"1264–1354","–1337":"–1337","7 February 1337":"7. helmikuuta 1337","from 1325 to 1345":"vuodesta 1325 vuoteen 1345","1264":"1264","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1347":"1347","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1354":"1354","about 1300":"noin 1300","Skerry, County Antrim, Ireland":"Skerry, County Antrim, Irlanti","Tir-Eoghain, Tyrone , Ireland":"Tyrone, County Galway, Irlant